<span id="v.iv.ix.xxx-p1"></span> <span class="c11"><span
id="v.iv.ix.xxx-p1.1"></span>Chapter 30.—</span>58.  Another Julianus of
Marcelliana <span id="fr_1838"></span>[1839](#fn_1838.md) said:  "If a man
can serve two masters, God and mammon, <span
id="fr_1839"></span>[1840](#fn_1839.md) then baptism also can serve two,
the Christian and the heretic." <span
id="fr_1840"></span>[1841](#fn_1840.md)

<span id="v.iv.ix.xxx-p5"></span>59.  Truly, if it can serve the
self-restrained and the covetous man, the sober and the drunken, the
well-affectioned and the murderer, why should it not also serve the
Christian and the heretic?—whom, indeed, it does not really serve; but
it ministers to them, and is administered by them, for salvation to
those who use it right, and for judgment to such as use it wrong.

